{#n70}
[p:Buchanan] confesses that [p:Rizzio] was ugly; but it may be inferred, from the narration of that author, that he was young. He says, that on the return of the duke of [l:Savoy] to [l:Turin], [p:Rizzio] was _in adolescentiae vigore;_ in the vigour of youth. Now that event happened only a few years before, lib. xvii. cap. 44. That Bothwel was young appears, among many other invincible proofs, from [p:Mary]'s instructions to the bishop of Dumblain, her ambassador at [l:Paris]; where she says, that in 1559, only eight years before, he was _very young._ He might therefore have been about thirty when he married her. See [p:Keith]'s History, p. 388. From the appendix to the _epistolae regum Scotorum,_ it appears, by authentic documents, that Patrick, earl of [l:Bothwel], father to [p:James], who espoused queen [p:Mary], was alive, till near the year 1560. [p:Buchanan], by a mistake, which has been long ago corrected, calls him [p:James].

