{#n173}
[p:Mary]'s complaint of the queen's partiality in admitting Murray to a conference was a mere pretext in order to break off the conference. She indeed employs that reason in her order for that purpose ([see Goodall, vol. ii. p. 184]), but in her private letter, her commissioners are directed to make use of that order to prevent her honour from being attacked, Goodall, vol. ii. p. 183. It was therefore the accusation only she was afraid of. Murray was the least obnoxious of all her enemies: He was abroad when her subjects rebelled and reduced her to captivity: He had only accepted of the regency, when voluntarily proffered him by the nation. His being admitted to queen [p:Elizabeth]'s presence was therefore a very bad foundation for a quarrel, or for breaking off the conference; and was plainly a mere pretence.

