{#n41}
By Murden's state papers, published after the writing of this history, it appears, that an agreement had been made between [p:Elizabeth] and the regent for the delivering up of [p:Mary] to him. The queen afterwards sent down Killigrew to the earl of Marre when regent, offering to put [p:Mary] into his hands. Killigrew was instructed to take good security from the regent, that that queen should be tried for her crimes, and that the sentence should be executed upon her. It appears that Marre rejected the offer; because we hear no more of it.

