{#n23}
That the queen's negociations for marrying the duke of [l:Anjou] were not feigned nor political, appears clearly from many circumstances; particularly from a passage in [p:Dr. Forbes]'s manuscript collections, at present in the possession of lord Royston. She there enjoins [p:Walsingham], before he opens the treaty, to examine the person of the duke; and as that prince had lately recovered from the small pox, she desires her ambassador to consider, whether he yet retained so much of his good looks, as that a woman could fix her affections on him. Had she not been in earnest, and had she only meant to amuse the public or the court of [l:France], this circumstance was of no moment.

