{#n20}
In the second of [p:Richard II]. it was enacted that in loans, which the king shall require of his subjects, upon letters of Privy Seal, such as have _reasonable_ excuse of not lending, may there be received without further summons, travel, or grief. See Cotton's Abridg. p. 170. By this law, the king's prerogative of exacting loans was ratified; and what ought to be deemed a _reasonable_ excuse was still left in his own breast, to determine.

